Almost Human, Fox US, premiere, review
Is this RoboCop-like sci-fi series from the JJ Abrams production line too mechanical for its own good? 2
Michael Ealy as the android cop in the JJ Abrams-produced series Almost Human Photo: Fox	By Jonathan Bernstein
7:24AM GMT 18 Nov 2013
Comments
CONTAINS SPOILERS The future doesn’t look good. The streets are awash in drugs and weapons supplied by an elusive but ruthlessly efficient criminal organisation with corporate ties. The crime rate has ballooned by 400%. The police are undermanned to the extent they need to turn to technology for help. Enter the advanced combat model android. That’s the set-up for Robocop, the 1987 Paul Verhoeven film whose widely un-anticipated reboot appears early next year. By an amazing coincidence, it’s also the foundation on which Almost Human, the new man-and-machine buddy cop TV series from JJ Abrams’ genre assembly line, is built. Beyond introducing a world where the pairing of human and robot law enforcement officers is mandatory, Almost Human quickly stops gnawing on the flesh of Robocop. It then starts raiding the corpse of Alien Nation, the 1988 movie teaming James Caan’s hard-ass lawman with a prosthetic-swamped Mandy Patinkin as his chatty, oversensitive partner from another planet. Filling Caan’s shoes is Karl Urban, whose Jon Kennex is a walking compendium of cop cliches. He’s a grouchy, brooding, gravel-voiced, pill-popping mess. Back in his renegade glory days, against the advice of his android partners, he lead his human team into an ambush, from which only he was able to crawl away, albeit minus most of a leg. He spent the subsequent two years wallowing in self-hate and and survivor’s guilt - much of which, since he was fitted with a synthetic leg, is directed at his own body. He hates his leg! Within seconds of returning to duty, Kennex’s anti-robot prejudice surfaces - ”A human partner was good enough for my father and it’s good enough for me!”- and he shoves his new cyborg buddy out of a moving car where it’s smashed to bits by oncoming traffic. His sympathetic boss (a baleful-looking Lili Taylor) orders him to shape up. Kennex consults the weird squirrely man who toils down in the basement of the robotics department (The Office’s Mackenzie Crook). The weird man unwraps Dorian (Michael Ealy), a discontinued model, an early brand of robot cop put on ice for being too emotional, too unpredictable, too human. And there’s the show: the flesh and blood guy is all repressed anger and inability to deal with his issues; the synthetic one is happy to declare, “I was made to feel.” The robot-as-race-metaphor is gingerly addressed with Ealy, a black actor, recoiling from his partner’s derisive description of him as “synthetic”. When Kennex, impressed by the android’s deductive skills, warms up to him enough to say, “You’re not like the rest of them,” Ealy’s Dorian replies, “I know you think I’m supposed to take that as a compliment.”
