Flood crisis: councils 'reluctant to accept Army help', says defence secretary
Philip Hammond claims military had to 'push itself' on council leaders during flood crisis
By Matthew Holehouse, Political Correspondent
11:22AM GMT 16 Feb 2014
Follow Councils were reluctant to accept help from the Army during the floods, the defence secretary has said. Philip Hammond said the military had to “push” itself on council leaders. He admitted a new policy of having Army officers supporting civilian leaders was the direct result of his public admonishment by a furious flood warden in the flooded village of Wraysbury. Members of the armed forces place sandbags outside a residential property in Wraysbury (BLOOMBERG)
“We offered troops quite a long while ago to civil authorities that wanted them. What we’ve done over the past ten days is push them a bit more aggressively,” he said. “We needed to push ourselves a bit more on the civilian authorities.”
