In future crises military officers would be embedded in the ‘gold command’ response headquarters at an earlier stage, he said. He defended ministers who visited flood-stricken areas in wellington boots from accusations of flood tourism. The public rebuke he received from Su Burrows, a furious flood warden in Wraysbury, led to him asking the Government’s COBRA crisis committee to deploy the Army differently. “There’s been a lot of talk of politicians doing flood tourism, but encouraging us to stay in Whitehall rather than getting out on the ground would be a very, very bad idea,” he said. “There’s been a lot of criticism of politicians in wellies, but it’s only because I went to Wraysbury and listened to what people were saying that we were able to develop this new approach of using the Army in this community support role.”
Troops being withdrawn from Afghanistan and Germany will be deployed on more ‘homeland resilience’ operations in future, he said. Some 3,000 troops have been deployed to build flood defences, and 5,000 are on standby, Mr Hammond said. Mr Hammond said Ed Miliband was not “saying anything new” by calling for climate change to be treated as an issue of national security. It is already classified as a “strategic threat” by the National Security Committee, Mr Hammond said. “It is a national security issue,” he said. Climate change had contributed to recent flooding, he said: “Climate change is clearly happening. It’s clearly a factor in the weather patterns that we’re seeing.”
He refused to rule out building on flood plains in future, after it emerged council are planning to put houses on areas that are currently submerged, saying flood defence must be balanced with economic growth and “maintaining people’s standard of living.” Weather
